column1: Rule 1: Modifiers containing both amino and carboxylic acid groups, especially in an amino acid structure, tend to result in a high yield.
column2: Rule 2: Modifiers with a benzoic acid structure and additional electron-withdrawing groups such as nitro or bromo tend to result in a high yield.
column3: Rule 3: Modifiers with a pyridine ring and additional electron-withdrawing groups tend to result in a low yield.
column4: Rule 4: Modifiers with a hydroxyl group on a phenyl ring tend to result in a high yield.
column5: Rule 5: Modifiers with a sulfanyl group tend to result in a high yield.
column6: Rule 6: Modifiers with a formyl group on a benzoic acid structure tend to result in a low yield.
column7: Rule 7: Modifiers with multiple ether linkages tend to result in a low yield.
column8: Rule 8: Modifiers with a trifluoroacetyl group tend to result in a low yield.
column9: Rule 9: Modifiers with a long aliphatic chain without additional functional groups tend to result in a low yield.
column10: Rule 10: Modifiers with a pyrazole ring tend to result in a high yield.
column11: Rule 11: Modifiers with a phenyl ring substituted with electron-donating groups such as methoxy tend to result in a high yield.
column12: Rule 12: Modifiers with a carboxylic acid group adjacent to a phenyl ring and additional electron-donating groups tend to result in a high yield.
column13: Rule 13: Modifiers with a hydroxyl group on an aliphatic chain tend to result in a low yield.
column14: Rule 14: Modifiers with a formyl group on a phenyl ring without additional electron-donating groups tend to result in a low yield.
column15: Rule 15: Modifiers with a pyridine ring and additional electron-donating groups tend to result in a high yield.
